WEBVTT

00:00.002 --> 00:02.905
I will just mention again something I brought up last week.

00:03.045 --> 00:10.933
We have started this new series called Long Journey Home and we're looking at the trek of the children of Israel from Egypt to the Promised Land.

00:11.493 --> 00:16.138
And I suggested to you that as we go through this, that maybe you want to keep your own travel log.

00:16.698 --> 00:21.463
Now what I mean by that is I would encourage you to be reading the story on your own at home.

00:22.003 --> 00:29.010
And as you're reading it, be praying about it because I think one of the things we learn from the voyage of the children of Israel, that trek,

00:29.186 --> 00:34.754
is how much of their journey parallels the journey that we make as followers of Jesus.

00:35.334 --> 00:44.066
And so as you read that, be perfectly thinking about what is there here that I can learn that will be helpful in my own journey as a Christian.

00:44.687 --> 00:49.874
And as you think about that as Lord brings things to mind, I would like you to keep a journal.

00:50.114 --> 00:52.177
And just write down, what are those observations?

00:52.257 --> 01:00.147
Now, I understand that for many of our women, this journal may have a lot of pages, including flowers and highlights and things like that.

01:00.748 --> 01:03.652
And many of our men, it's going to say yes, no, yes, no.

01:04.293 --> 01:04.954
That's okay.

01:04.974 --> 01:08.258
Whatever journaling means for you, just go ahead and do that.

01:08.358 --> 01:14.386
But track with what you're learning as you're reading about the children of Israel and their journey.

01:16.066 --> 01:23.974
A couple of weekends ago, Burnett and I had a chance to be in Oregon because two of our sons live there, all the grandkids live there.

01:24.394 --> 01:26.717
And so we try to get down a few times a year.

01:26.737 --> 01:36.066
And if you ever paid attention as you're driving through Oregon, there are places you'll come across these historical markers along the road.

01:36.787 --> 01:43.954
And the signs will point out for you the route that you're traveling on was part of the original Oregon Trail.

01:44.450 --> 01:53.163
that hazardous trail of 2,000 miles that once was traversed by these hearty pioneers that were looking to make a new life in the West.

01:54.365 --> 02:00.594
Most young adults who were in school in the 1990s are probably familiar with this game, right?

02:00.815 --> 02:01.656
Oregon Trail.

02:02.297 --> 02:11.271
And in order to win this game, this simulation, you had to overcome numerous obstacles that settlers might have encountered as they're on the trail.

02:11.431 --> 02:13.554
And if you failed,

02:13.698 --> 02:17.182
to pass the tests, you died.

02:17.242 --> 02:18.664
That was very sad.

02:18.704 --> 02:27.135
And so I know all of my kids would come home going through cyber grief because their family had just died in the Oregon Trail.

02:29.137 --> 02:32.862
For the actual pioneers though, that danger was very real.

02:33.603 --> 02:36.487
In fact, here is how one history site describes it.

02:37.648 --> 02:42.354
The trail was so deadly, it's been called the nation's longest graveyard.

02:43.234 --> 03:01.574
Some historians estimate that if you calculated the total number of people who died on the trail from 1840 to 1860, and then evenly spaced out all of the graves from Independence to Oregon City, you could place a grave every 50 yards over the entire 2000 mile trip.

03:02.756 --> 03:04.398
It's pretty staggering to think about.

03:06.079 --> 03:11.986
While disease accounted for a lot of those deaths, river crossings were also

03:12.290 --> 03:14.494
deadly serious endeavors.

03:14.534 --> 03:19.963
We don't think much about it because we get to big rivers and we just drive across bridges or we take ferries.

03:20.023 --> 03:27.756
And we don't realize experientially what a huge obstacle those rivers were for the people as they traveled west.

03:27.796 --> 03:31.562
But here is a little reenactment film I found from the 1950s.

03:32.724 --> 03:38.834
Crossing rivers and there were many between Missouri and Oregon was a tedious and sometimes dangerous undertaking.

03:39.266 --> 03:55.858
It took hours for the wagon train to cross a simple shallow forward, but crossing a deep fast running river could mean an eternity of unloading, caulking wagons, removing their wheels and floating them across the treacherous currents, then reloading them on the other side before moving off.

04:08.162 --> 04:11.907
The Lord of hosts will do battle for us.

04:16.292 --> 04:32.934
Behold his mighty hand.

04:32.954 --> 04:36.338
Kind of makes you appreciate how far computer graphics have come doesn't it?

04:37.666 --> 04:47.519
Well, today we're gonna talk about that story, the crossing of the Red Sea, and so I'll begin by just reading with you what actually happened.

04:47.539 --> 04:53.067
This comes from Exodus chapter 13 and 14, and so begins at verse 17.

04:54.709 --> 05:04.101
When Pharaoh finally let the people go, God did not lead them along the main road that runs through Philistine territory, even though that was the shortest route to the Promised Land.

05:05.143 --> 05:07.506
God said, if the people are faced with a battle,

05:07.874 --> 05:10.858
They might change their minds and return to Egypt.

05:10.878 --> 05:18.407
So God led them in a roundabout way through the wilderness toward the Red Sea, jumping down to Exodus 14.

05:19.348 --> 05:21.291
Then the Lord gave these instructions to Moses.

05:22.212 --> 05:27.018
Order the Israelites to turn back and camp by Pai Harahat.

05:27.038 --> 05:27.719
I can't say that.

05:28.180 --> 05:31.464
Hararoth, there you go, between McDoll and the sea.

05:31.964 --> 05:34.648
Camp there along the shore, cross from Baal Zephan.

05:35.268 --> 05:36.530
Then Pharaoh will think

05:36.802 --> 05:38.103
The Israelites are confused.

05:38.644 --> 05:39.785
They're trapped in the wilderness.

05:40.466 --> 05:43.649
And once again, I will harden Pharaoh's heart, and he will chase after you.

05:44.450 --> 05:48.774
I have planned this in order to display my glory through Pharaoh and his whole army.

05:49.615 --> 05:53.098
After this, the Egyptians will know that I am the Lord.

05:54.840 --> 06:00.366
When word reached the king of Egypt that the Israelites had fled, Pharaoh and his officials changed their minds.

06:01.186 --> 06:01.867
What have we done?

06:02.267 --> 06:04.850
Letting all those Israelite slaves get away, they asked.

06:05.250 --> 06:08.575
So Pharaoh harnesses chariot and called up his troops.

06:09.977 --> 06:14.985
As Pharaoh approached, the people of Israel looked up and panicked when they saw the Egyptians overtaking them.

06:15.807 --> 06:20.735
They cried out to the Lord and they said to Moses, why did you bring us out here to die in the wilderness?

06:21.315 --> 06:23.659
Weren't there enough graves for us in Egypt?

06:23.679 --> 06:24.661
What have you done to us?

06:25.382 --> 06:27.044
Why did you make us leave Egypt?

06:27.806 --> 06:30.810
Didn't we tell you this would happen while we were still in Egypt?

06:31.311 --> 06:33.074
We said, leave us alone.

06:33.282 --> 06:35.184
Let us be slaves to the Egyptians.

06:35.665 --> 06:39.569
It's better to be a slave in Egypt than a corpse in the wilderness.

06:42.212 --> 06:44.975
But Moses told the people, don't be afraid.

06:46.036 --> 06:49.940
Just stand still and watch the Lord rescue you today.

06:50.981 --> 06:53.544
The Egyptians you see today will never be seen again.

06:54.345 --> 06:56.828
The Lord himself will fight for you.

06:57.268 --> 06:58.930
Just stay calm.

07:00.226 --> 07:02.609
Then the Lord said to Moses, why are you crying out to me?

07:02.709 --> 07:06.775
Tell the people to get moving, pick up your staff, raise your hand over the sea.

07:07.356 --> 07:16.008
Divide the water so the Israelites can walk through the middle of the sea on dry ground and I will harden the hearts of the Egyptians and they will charge in after the Israelites.

07:17.169 --> 07:21.836
Then Moses raised his hand over the sea and the Lord opened up a path through the water with a strong east wind.

07:22.377 --> 07:29.266
The wind blew all that night turning the sea bed into dry land so the people of Israel walk through the middle of the sea on dry ground

07:29.346 --> 07:31.029
with walls of water on each side.

07:31.870 --> 07:37.861
Then the Egyptians, all of Pharaoh's horses, chariots, and cherry tears, chased them into the middle of the sea.

07:39.264 --> 07:51.826
Then the waters returned and covered all the chariots and charioteers, the entire army of Pharaoh, of all the Egyptians who had chased the Israelites into the sea, not a single one survived.

07:53.570 --> 08:00.098
The first thing I'd want to draw our attention to this morning is we think about this story and probably a story that you have heard numerous times before.

08:00.178 --> 08:02.862
If you went to Sunday school, I'm sure you had it in Sunday school.

08:03.322 --> 08:10.071
But one of the things I want to draw your attention to is this roundabout path that God took the people on.

08:10.111 --> 08:11.152
Did you notice that, right?

08:11.172 --> 08:11.713
The outset?

08:12.554 --> 08:20.123
We're told that the Lord chose to send Israel the long way toward their promised new homeland.

08:21.425 --> 08:22.226
And the reason

08:22.690 --> 08:25.813
was so that they would avoid meeting strong opposition.

08:27.695 --> 08:33.801
These people, if you think about it, they had spent generations as powerless slaves.

08:34.782 --> 08:36.825
These were not battle-hardened warriors.

08:36.865 --> 08:42.631
They didn't have any civilian militia that had been training for combat all these years.

08:43.171 --> 08:44.212
They were just slaves.

08:45.053 --> 08:49.938
They knew how to make bricks, but they did not know how to fight wars.

08:50.754 --> 08:53.658
I've been reading through a biography of John Adams recently.

08:53.738 --> 08:59.025
He was the second president of the United States, a key figure in the founding of our nation.

08:59.566 --> 09:03.692
And in that biography, it relates the Battle of Kips Bay.

09:05.174 --> 09:14.226
One of the first battles that happened when the revolution was beginning and the British decided to attack with this shock and awe campaign.

09:14.786 --> 09:21.374
British General Howe landed 9,000 of his highly trained British troops.

09:22.255 --> 09:27.501
He also unleashed this massive naval bombardment against the town.

09:28.683 --> 09:32.387
The American troops, of course, were comprised of just local militias.

09:33.248 --> 09:40.036
These were made up of farmers and shopkeepers and craftsmen who wanted to gain their freedom.

09:40.076 --> 09:44.722
They were highly motivated, but they never actually faced a real battle.

09:45.570 --> 09:53.260
And suddenly they are faced with real cannon fire breaking into their defenses, real bullets whipping over their heads.

09:54.462 --> 09:59.408
And as the story goes, the Americans almost immediately broke rank and began running.

10:00.369 --> 10:03.093
General Washington was furious.

10:03.874 --> 10:07.038
The record is that he was riding his horse back and forth.

10:07.098 --> 10:08.000
He had his whip out.

10:08.020 --> 10:12.946
He was trying to drive them in back to the line so they'd stop running away from the battle.

10:13.954 --> 10:17.018
even fired his pistol in the air, pulled his sword out at one point.

10:17.940 --> 10:26.372
But then finally realizing that he had completely lost control of his troops, he had to turn tail on his horse and simply follow his men as they retreated from the battle.

10:28.675 --> 10:31.339
That's the same kind of situation I think we have here with the Israelites.

10:32.561 --> 10:37.909
They are gonna be faced with battles, but the Lord knows at this point they have never had to face battle before.

10:38.550 --> 10:41.394
And so he takes them on this roundabout way.

10:43.650 --> 10:46.333
You know, I think sometimes that is true of our walk with God.

10:48.115 --> 10:51.700
I don't know what your experience was when you first became a follower of Jesus.

10:52.300 --> 10:57.887
Maybe even more so, this would be true if for you it was as a young adult or an older adult that you came to Christ.

10:58.668 --> 11:06.578
But I've had lots of friends that have related how when they first came to Jesus, it just seemed like, man, life was just incredible.

11:07.238 --> 11:10.162
You know, problems just went away.

11:10.274 --> 11:13.678
answers to prayer, miraculous answers to prayer, time and time again.

11:13.718 --> 11:15.560
And it was just so exciting.

11:17.303 --> 11:22.209
But then a day came when it seemed like the trials got harder.

11:23.670 --> 11:33.542
And rather than getting to skirt around them, it seemed that God let them know that it was time to face the trial and to fight.

11:35.705 --> 11:39.890
If that's been your experience, I just want to say that that's not because

11:40.130 --> 11:41.952
God has forsaken you.

11:43.595 --> 11:44.836
There is growth.

11:44.876 --> 11:49.522
There is deepening of faith that happens in the midst of trial.

11:51.124 --> 11:58.874
There are lots of verses that talk about the fact that how going through trial increases perseverance and perseverance builds character.

11:59.695 --> 12:01.878
Character brings forth godly fruit in our lives.

12:03.180 --> 12:07.826
But I think there are times when God knows you're not ready for the fight

12:08.482 --> 12:18.878
And he takes us on the roundabout way, but then there comes a point where he says, okay, we're going to do some character building in your life right now.

12:21.201 --> 12:23.585
Sometimes God will lead you around the struggle.

12:23.685 --> 12:26.469
Sometimes he will lead you through it.

12:28.132 --> 12:35.122
And now in the weeks ahead, we're going to see some of the lessons that God had for Israel and for us when it was time to fight.

12:35.906 --> 12:40.091
But at this early point in the journey, God leads them around the fight.

12:40.972 --> 12:44.817
The days are going to come soon enough when they're going to be called to step up.

12:46.199 --> 12:47.781
God would still be their deliverer.

12:47.801 --> 12:49.042
We're going to see that time and again.

12:49.082 --> 12:56.391
God is still their deliverer, but it is going to be a deliverance in the fight, not from the fight.

12:58.213 --> 13:05.362
Second thing I would draw our attention to is the place where God told them to set up camp.

13:06.082 --> 13:10.370
by that place that I can't pronounce between McDoll and the sea.

13:11.873 --> 13:14.879
Strategically, it wasn't a good location.

13:16.402 --> 13:21.312
In fact, in Pharaoh's eyes, it certainly looked like opportunity knocking.

13:23.095 --> 13:26.482
We learned that no sooner had Pharaoh let the people go,

13:26.978 --> 13:34.751
under duress, right, those ten horrible plagues, especially that final one, the death of the firstborn, that Pharaoh finally caved.

13:34.771 --> 13:37.415
He felt he had no choice but to let the people go.

13:37.455 --> 13:45.188
But then, as all those slaves have now escaped, he looks around and thinks, my goodness, what have we done?

13:46.170 --> 13:49.035
We just released our whole workforce here.

13:50.116 --> 13:53.522
And he has this change of heart and decides we need to go get those people back.

13:54.882 --> 14:00.370
And when he sees where they are camping, he thinks this isn't going to be too difficult.

14:01.953 --> 14:08.883
I think it's pretty safe to assume that Pharaoh had some scouts that were keeping tabs on this mass migration of slaves as they were leaving.

14:08.923 --> 14:16.455
And according to their reports, it would appear that these stupid slaves had got themselves lost.

14:17.096 --> 14:20.821
No sooner had they got out there than they got themselves lost.

14:22.103 --> 14:23.986
And yet the Lord has told Moses that

14:24.322 --> 14:25.544
This is all part of his plan.

14:26.766 --> 14:29.650
In fact, they weren't where they were because they were lost.

14:29.690 --> 14:31.994
They were where they were because God put them there.

14:32.495 --> 14:33.937
He had led them to that location.

14:35.680 --> 14:43.051
So while Pharaoh assumes that his dumb slaves don't know where they're going, God says, no, I have a surprise in store.

14:44.574 --> 14:52.306
Now I'm guessing that Moses, looking around at where they're camping, he had to be saying to himself, you know, Lord, is this really a good idea?

14:53.090 --> 14:55.633
because it feels like we don't have a lot of options.

14:56.555 --> 15:03.724
I've got people here that you and I both agree they don't know how to fight and we've got an army coming from that direction and we've got nothing but water behind us.

15:04.966 --> 15:09.372
And yet the Lord says you're exactly where I want you right now.

15:10.894 --> 15:16.722
So as anticipated Pharaoh decides he's going to try to recapture those slaves, thinks it's going to be easy.

15:17.474 --> 15:20.899
We find out that it's not just Pharaoh who thinks that they're lost.

15:20.919 --> 15:24.024
The children of Israel themselves recognize they're in a bad spot.

15:25.346 --> 15:26.608
They can see the dust.

15:26.648 --> 15:29.151
They can see horses and chariots coming toward them.

15:30.694 --> 15:37.684
They realize too late that they are trapped and they know something about Pharaoh's cruelty when he's angered.

15:37.704 --> 15:42.932
They have lived his slaves for generations and they know how their masters are when they are angry.

15:44.895 --> 15:47.218
So desperate, frightened,

15:47.778 --> 15:51.262
They turn on Moses, which is a bad habit.

15:51.282 --> 15:55.247
We're gonna see repeated on this journey over and over again.

15:55.307 --> 15:57.069
And here's what happens.

15:58.171 --> 16:03.017
They cried out to the Lord and they said to Moses, why did you bring us out here to die in the wilderness?

16:03.397 --> 16:05.920
Weren't there enough graves for us in Egypt?

16:08.503 --> 16:17.074
You know, I think it's easy for us living on this side of history to smirk just a little bit at their responses.

16:17.922 --> 16:22.126
that they weren't more noble, that they weren't more faith-filled.

16:22.967 --> 16:25.109
I mean, they'd been through all those plagues.

16:25.149 --> 16:29.533
They had seen how God had brought them out of a place that they thought they could never escape.

16:30.294 --> 16:37.701
And here they are, the first sign of trouble, and they're turning on Moses and saying, you know, we could have died just as well back there as out here.

16:37.861 --> 16:38.982
What have you done to us?

16:42.005 --> 16:47.410
But you know, I think we also understand that when trials come, there is this very human tendency

16:47.970 --> 16:50.133
to look around for someone to blame.

16:51.415 --> 16:52.596
Who can I pin this on?

16:54.619 --> 17:07.216
We can even be tempted to want to return back to a bad situation because it seems less scary to face the bad that we know rather than moving into the potential dangers of the unknown.

17:08.318 --> 17:09.379
And that was true of these people.

17:10.320 --> 17:13.144
They looked around and they said, you know, I think maybe life was better as a slave.

17:13.905 --> 17:17.490
Could we just wind the clock back and go back to that status?

17:19.458 --> 17:21.260
You know, the thing is we like to stay in control.

17:22.561 --> 17:23.482
Or maybe I'm the only one.

17:24.683 --> 17:26.025
I bet you all like to stay in control.

17:26.906 --> 17:28.708
We like to know how things are going to play out.

17:30.490 --> 17:37.096
But I've also learned in my own life, and I've watched lots of other people, that our control is often deceptive.

17:38.518 --> 17:46.226
Some of the goals that we set our hopes on to find fulfillment so often turn out to be mirages.

17:46.914 --> 17:53.666
The thing that we thought was going to make life worth living, we get there and life still seems to have empty places.

17:55.449 --> 18:03.964
The sacrifices that we're willing to make to get the things that we want so often end up sacrificing too much.

18:06.588 --> 18:12.178
Sometimes the modes that we have used to cope when life got hard

18:13.186 --> 18:23.962
Change from being just a coping mechanism into being a new kind of master, a new kind of addiction that enslaves us and won't let us go.

18:24.002 --> 18:40.466
God in His mercy may take us to a place, a point of crisis, where we suddenly realize that things are beyond our control, a place where we run out of options.

18:41.762 --> 18:45.047
We're the things that we thought were gonna make us free in our own plan.

18:45.147 --> 18:48.952
We suddenly face the reality that I'm not free.

18:50.835 --> 18:52.137
It didn't do what it promised.

18:55.381 --> 19:02.090
And if we're fortunate, we reach a place where we recognize that if God doesn't save us, nothing else will.

19:03.593 --> 19:06.316
And in those moments, we can either cry out to him.

19:07.098 --> 19:10.322
We can lean in and say, Lord, I need you.

19:11.810 --> 19:14.073
Or we can turn back to the things that enslave us.

19:16.156 --> 19:18.820
And I bet you've seen it happen in people's lives.

19:19.841 --> 19:23.366
They get right to that crisis point and you think they're about to have that breakthrough.

19:24.628 --> 19:26.611
And suddenly they just turn around and say, you know what?

19:27.632 --> 19:29.635
At least I know who the master was over here.

19:31.998 --> 19:35.102
I was looking at some of the material from Celebrate Recovery.

19:35.122 --> 19:37.005
We have a Celebrate Recovery group that meets here.

19:37.085 --> 19:40.530
It's modeled after AA, the 12 Steps.

19:40.738 --> 19:43.742
And I noted what step number one is for them.

19:45.204 --> 19:48.669
People with hurts and hang ups and habits that have taken control.

19:49.370 --> 20:00.025
Step number one, we admitted that we were powerless over our addictions and compulsive behaviors that our lives had become unmanageable.

20:01.447 --> 20:08.978
Step one in a person's life in breaking free from slavery is recognizing that I can't control the slave master.

20:10.018 --> 20:15.144
I'm going to need someone bigger than me if I'm ever going to find freedom.

20:18.007 --> 20:25.595
Now the solution, the salvation, the deliverance for Israel was something that they could not imagine being possible.

20:26.876 --> 20:34.064
If you had given them a fill in the blank as to God will deliver us by blank, none of them would have got this answer.

20:35.746 --> 20:39.250
God opens up a path through the sea

20:39.330 --> 20:41.193
and let them pass through on dry land.

20:42.495 --> 20:50.988
And then the sea closes up and the power that had enslaved them was cut off, never more to be their master.

20:52.089 --> 20:53.091
That chase was over.

20:54.673 --> 21:08.594
That didn't mean there weren't still battles to be fought, but there had been a definitive crossing over from a land of slavery to a journey now as free people

21:09.154 --> 21:10.275
to a land of promise.

21:12.297 --> 21:20.024
I was working on this passage, and I came across, I thought it was a beautiful quote that was recounted by the late Timothy Keller.

21:20.064 --> 21:26.590
He recounts being a young student, and he heard a talk by British theologian Alec Motier.

21:27.331 --> 21:29.293
And here's part of what Dr. Motier said.

21:31.315 --> 21:36.180
Think of what an Israelite would say on the way to Canaan after passing through the Red Sea.

21:37.521 --> 21:38.802
If you asked an Israelite,

21:39.170 --> 21:39.811
Who are you?

21:39.851 --> 21:47.098
He might reply, I was in a foreign land under the sentence of death and in bondage.

21:48.359 --> 21:55.866
But I took shelter under the blood of the lamb, and our mediator let us out, and we crossed over.

21:56.907 --> 22:01.552
Now we're on our way to the promised land, though we're not there yet.

22:02.893 --> 22:08.018
That's exactly what a Christian says, almost word for word.

22:08.706 --> 22:11.629
I love how he makes that parallel for us.

22:13.391 --> 22:18.617
The deliverance of Israel from their slavery in Egypt is captured in two powerful images.

22:18.677 --> 22:29.268
Last week we considered Passover, that deliverance from death by the people placing faith in the seemingly powerless blood of a lamb.

22:30.509 --> 22:38.578
And now we have this image, their deliverance from enslavement by a miraculous crossing that left

22:38.690 --> 22:40.392
the land of slavery behind.

22:42.374 --> 22:46.900
In both cases, the people had to take a step of faith.

22:48.501 --> 22:51.845
They couldn't defeat the destroyer on the night of Passover.

22:52.826 --> 22:54.829
In fact, they were told just to stay in your home.

22:56.070 --> 22:57.031
Don't even go outside.

22:57.111 --> 22:59.394
You can't face this on your own.

23:00.235 --> 23:06.162
And the only protection between them and death was their willingness to do what God had told them

23:06.242 --> 23:08.985
to apply the blood of the Lamb to their doorposts.

23:10.707 --> 23:20.457
Well, now here they are, trapped between Pharaoh's chariots and the sea, and it's evident once again that their own strength is not going to deliver them.

23:21.118 --> 23:25.523
They can't escape nor can they defeat their masters.

23:27.005 --> 23:35.634
And their only hope was to step in faith through the channel that God had created, and in doing so, cross over

23:36.066 --> 23:36.987
into a land of freedom.

23:40.092 --> 23:44.159
Do you know what sets Christianity apart from every other world religion?

23:45.882 --> 23:49.587
We might sum it up as, how do you cross over?

23:51.410 --> 23:58.622
In every other religious system, the way you cross over is the same way Oregon pioneers tackled rivers.

23:59.744 --> 24:01.266
You swim hard.

24:02.402 --> 24:13.176
You do all that you can to keep your head above water, you fight the current, and if you do it well enough, you hope you'll be lucky enough to crawl up the bank on the far side.

24:14.818 --> 24:19.605
Christianity says that plan will never work.

24:19.625 --> 24:24.251
Here's what the Apostle Paul wrote, Romans 323, this from the new living translation.

24:24.631 --> 24:26.694
He says, everyone has sinned.

24:27.695 --> 24:29.778
We all fall short,

24:30.210 --> 24:32.553
of God's glorious standard.

24:33.715 --> 24:41.766
I think that idea of falling short isn't popular in a culture that is obsessed with developing positive self-esteem.

24:42.888 --> 24:45.652
I don't want anyone telling me that I'm gonna come up short.

24:47.394 --> 24:53.703
And it can be an especially hard thing for modern people to think of themselves as sinners.

24:54.725 --> 24:58.450
It seems like kind of a harsh word to be using about ourselves.

24:59.394 --> 25:01.156
But let's try a little thought experiment.

25:02.657 --> 25:12.727
For just a minute in your mind, I want you to think of the lowest slime ball of an individual that you have ever known or heard of.

25:13.868 --> 25:16.390
Just get that picture, get that name in your mind.

25:17.051 --> 25:18.552
Who is that horrible person?

25:19.293 --> 25:22.856
And let's figure out where we're going to put them here on Morality River.

25:24.278 --> 25:29.042
There they are over there in Wickedville, just a bad, bad person.

25:30.114 --> 25:39.062
All right, now, I want you to think for a minute about the most virtuous person you've ever known, ever heard of.

25:39.883 --> 25:43.827
I mean, in your mind, this person defines a saint.

25:45.028 --> 25:50.954
And let's put them over here on the other bank of Morality River.

25:51.054 --> 25:52.795
They live near a perfect town.

25:54.937 --> 25:59.762
Now, because of their incredible discipline,

26:00.450 --> 26:03.755
They're stamina, they have made it to the far shore.

26:03.775 --> 26:05.578
In your mind, these are people who have made it.

26:06.540 --> 26:12.790
What I want you to do now is I want you to decide where you would put yourself in the river.

26:14.232 --> 26:14.833
Where would you be?

26:15.674 --> 26:23.026
Now, my guess is that's probably going to be somewhere farther across than that nasty guy.

26:23.927 --> 26:28.114
I mean, he's a bad person and it's not hard for you to go, well, I'm better than him.

26:29.282 --> 26:39.014
Now, unless you are a delusional narcissist, you're probably going to put yourself at least a few strokes behind misperfect.

26:42.138 --> 26:54.354
But you know, I can guarantee you that if you could get access to misperfect personal journal, where all of her innermost thoughts

26:54.722 --> 26:59.728
and the history of her whole life, everything that she's ever done or said or thought.

26:59.768 --> 27:10.041
If you could lay your hands on that and you page through it all the way and you made a list, you would discover that she too hasn't quite hit the other shore.

27:12.364 --> 27:16.329
And you know what you have discovered in the process of this little thought experiment?

27:17.671 --> 27:19.814
You would agree with the Apostle Paul.

27:21.015 --> 27:23.218
Everyone falls short.

27:24.066 --> 27:27.790
None of us on our own can get across that river.

27:28.150 --> 27:29.872
Some of us get farther across than others.

27:30.913 --> 27:32.154
Some of us are pretty strong swimmers.

27:32.194 --> 27:32.975
We look good.

27:33.816 --> 27:35.277
We just don't get to the other side.

27:37.980 --> 27:40.222
Here's what makes Christianity unique.

27:41.884 --> 27:44.266
Not that it points out the truth about our shortcomings.

27:44.286 --> 27:45.367
Some of the people get stuck there.

27:45.847 --> 27:48.330
Go on man, the Bible is just all about how people sin.

27:49.031 --> 27:51.173
Well, it's good to know where you're at.

27:51.193 --> 27:52.594
Let's not deceive ourselves.

27:53.058 --> 27:54.761
But that's not the most important thing.

27:54.781 --> 27:59.729
The most important thing is that it says that God has opened a path across for us.

28:01.191 --> 28:05.378
He hasn't left us drowning in the river or stuck over there in Wickedville.

28:05.438 --> 28:07.401
He has opened a way across.

28:08.022 --> 28:11.608
And it's a path that doesn't depend on our efforts, but on his grace.

28:11.668 --> 28:13.531
Here's what it says in John chapter five.

28:14.011 --> 28:18.098
Whoever hears my word and believes him who sent me has eternal life.

28:18.722 --> 28:23.047
He does not come into judgment, but has passed from death to life.

28:23.267 --> 28:27.171
That's Jesus' words, or this Ephesians chapter two.

28:28.172 --> 28:30.595
God saved you by His grace when you believed.

28:31.476 --> 28:32.337
He took a step of faith.

28:33.478 --> 28:34.700
And you can't take credit for this.

28:35.461 --> 28:37.182
It is a gift from God.

28:37.643 --> 28:43.590
Salvation is not a reward for the good things we've done, so none of us can boast about it.

28:45.331 --> 28:47.634
None of the Israelites could get to the opposite bank

28:48.034 --> 28:51.719
They're at the Red Sea and say, man, are we good river crossers or what?

28:52.099 --> 28:54.302
Did you see the way I came through there?

28:55.965 --> 28:58.368
All they could do was look back and say, what a gift.

28:59.349 --> 29:10.865
What an amazing gift that when we were out of options, when there was nowhere to go, when we didn't have the strength to get ourselves across, God did something for us that we could not do for ourselves.

29:12.627 --> 29:17.874
I thought it might be good as we're thinking about this, just to listen to one testimony.

29:18.338 --> 29:20.560
of what it's like to cross over.

29:21.401 --> 29:23.343
Last week I sat down with Steve Lopes.

29:23.443 --> 29:24.644
We had a great conversation.

29:24.684 --> 29:26.506
Here's just a little snippet of that.

29:27.647 --> 29:28.989
We lived in Port Townsend.

29:29.509 --> 29:37.797
I was trying to run a blacksmithing business, which, who in their right mind wants to do, thinks they could make a living doing that.

29:38.878 --> 29:46.546
I was kind of scared because of all the responsibilities, mortgage, kids, this and that, running a business

29:46.786 --> 29:50.131
I was probably drinking too much.

29:50.191 --> 29:59.523
There were Fridays where my wife would have to call me at the tavern and say, your dinner's in the oven, I'm going to bed.

29:59.564 --> 30:02.367
You know, Satan had a hole in me.

30:02.668 --> 30:04.270
There's no doubt in my mind.

30:04.671 --> 30:09.077
And my wife would say, what is wrong with you?

30:09.117 --> 30:11.420
Why are you doing this?

30:11.440 --> 30:15.986
And I go, I don't know.

30:16.386 --> 30:17.768
I'm a knucklehead.

30:19.209 --> 30:24.976
Anyway, one night I had this dream that I wrecked a bunch of cars.

30:26.257 --> 30:36.148
I ran somebody over trying to get home and there was a policeman in this dream who looked a lot like Jesus.

30:38.110 --> 30:41.915
And he said, you're in big trouble.

30:41.935 --> 30:44.978
You know, it did not leave me that dream.

30:45.058 --> 30:49.024
And it made me start thinking, what are you doing?

30:50.325 --> 30:52.609
I mean, you're talking about Pharaoh's army.

30:52.689 --> 30:54.992
I mean, I'm seeing Pharaoh's army come.

30:55.433 --> 30:58.236
And it's not looking good.

31:00.059 --> 31:08.691
Then once Sunday, this Christian midwife, Carol Gouchy, she said, why don't you come play music with us?

31:09.452 --> 31:12.136
And I like, look, I don't know your music.

31:12.216 --> 31:13.618
I don't know anything about

31:13.794 --> 31:15.656
I'm not a Christian.

31:15.676 --> 31:20.122
I'm actually, now I have a sober look at myself.

31:20.222 --> 31:22.245
I'm actually not a very nice person.

31:23.126 --> 31:29.714
And for some reason, I just grabbed my manal in and came along and God came into my life that moment.

31:30.235 --> 31:35.041
I took a step with him and he was there.

31:35.662 --> 31:36.943
I stopped being fearful.

31:37.524 --> 31:42.130
I started seeing things like the blessings I had rather than the

31:42.306 --> 31:45.431
balls that I was juggling, trying to keep juggled in the air.

31:46.913 --> 31:49.877
I stepped into life from death.

31:49.937 --> 31:55.526
I stepped out of fear into, you know, it says, come under me.

31:55.566 --> 31:58.370
You were burdened and heavy laden and I will give you rest.

31:58.490 --> 31:59.772
I stepped into his rest.

32:04.019 --> 32:11.570
We are early in the journey here, but the journey begins with that crossing over.

32:13.058 --> 32:17.764
And so I just have to ask you this morning, which side of the river are you standing on?

32:19.446 --> 32:30.920
Maybe you're here, you're sitting in a church service, you are surrounded, you assume, by people of faith, but you know in your heart that you are still standing on the Egypt side of the river.

32:32.242 --> 32:33.944
You have not crossed over.

32:35.466 --> 32:38.610
And maybe slavery is a good description of how you feel.

32:39.746 --> 32:49.562
Like Steve, maybe he wouldn't say it out loud to other people, but inside he could feel that I don't know why I'm doing the things that I'm doing.

32:49.642 --> 32:51.825
I don't know why I'm stuck where I'm stuck.

32:54.670 --> 32:57.775
Maybe you relate to that sense of you're in trouble.

33:00.138 --> 33:07.570
I just want to say the same God who opened the Red Sea to provide escape is ready and willing

33:07.746 --> 33:10.249
to open a wave of escape for you as well.

33:11.470 --> 33:22.362
No matter what the past is, no matter what the things are that haunt you or make you feel unworthy, God did not bring the people through the river because they were also noble.

33:22.382 --> 33:25.866
In fact, you saw them standing on the banks going, we should have just died back in Egypt.

33:26.246 --> 33:30.010
It's not because they were that commendable, but it's because he loved them.

33:31.892 --> 33:34.975
And the step begins with simply surrendering to him.

33:36.597 --> 33:37.458
Saying, Lord, I need you?

33:38.370 --> 33:40.493
And I'm willing to let you become the leader.

33:41.455 --> 33:45.120
I'm willing to let you take me where I need to go because I can't do it on my own.

33:47.224 --> 33:52.071
Now, maybe you would say, Tim, I'm working hard on this.

33:52.251 --> 33:52.872
I really am.

33:52.892 --> 33:55.276
I'm working hard to be a good Christian.

33:56.378 --> 33:58.140
I'm trying to do all the right things.

33:58.241 --> 34:02.267
And yeah, there have been some failures on my past, but I'm working.

34:02.367 --> 34:04.370
I'm doing my best to make up for them.

34:04.674 --> 34:08.179
I'm kind of paying God back because I know I owe him big time.

34:08.199 --> 34:13.866
And if we're talking about crossing the river, I am swimming the best that I can.

34:13.906 --> 34:17.191
And I'm just hoping that someday it's good enough.

34:19.534 --> 34:26.943
I'd just say if you think that being a Christian is something that you have to work to become, then you don't understand what Jesus has done for you.

34:29.727 --> 34:31.890
We don't make ourselves Christians.

34:32.642 --> 34:35.366
We accept the gift Jesus has offered.

34:37.248 --> 34:40.673
If you've done that, if you've accepted that gift, then you have crossed over.

34:42.976 --> 34:46.421
There's still a journey ahead, okay?

34:46.441 --> 34:49.866
You're not done, but you're on the other side of the river.

34:51.488 --> 34:54.132
And it's a gift that is offered to us.

34:55.914 --> 35:01.522
And that's why Jesus could tell his followers that he could offer them peace and rest

35:01.602 --> 35:10.234
and life because they were following him, not that it was always easy and yet there was peace even in the difficulty.

35:12.718 --> 35:20.469
Now I'm gonna guess that on a Sunday morning like this, probably a lot of us, maybe most of us would say, I've accepted that gift.

35:21.350 --> 35:24.275
I have crossed over, I know that I've crossed over.

35:25.937 --> 35:29.522
Maybe it's been a long time since the crossing happened and maybe,

35:29.858 --> 35:31.701
You've gotten weary on the journey.

35:31.761 --> 35:36.728
We're gonna see a lot of that as we move forward with Israel, of people that get weary on the journey.

35:38.711 --> 35:46.683
But you know, something that happens again and again in the history of Israel is they keep getting reminded that God brought you through the Red Sea.

35:48.486 --> 35:56.058
You may feel you've hit a dead end, you may feel that you're out of options, you may feel you can't go forward any farther, but then they say, but don't forget about the Red Sea.

35:57.480 --> 35:58.962
God has brought you here,

35:59.458 --> 36:03.564
The same God that brought you across is not going to leave you now.

36:04.124 --> 36:06.147
He is not going to fail you.

36:06.167 --> 36:12.095
I hope that Steve's story, maybe it was a good reminder of your own story.

36:12.936 --> 36:15.700
Whatever that experience was for you of crossing over.

36:17.983 --> 36:26.254
It was John Newton, the one time slave trader who penned those beautiful words to amazing grace.

36:28.437 --> 36:28.978
A tribute.

36:29.602 --> 36:31.304
really to his own crossing over.

36:33.327 --> 36:34.108
Amazing grace.

36:35.490 --> 36:39.716
How sweet the sound that saved a wretch like me.

36:41.158 --> 36:47.566
I once was lost, but now I've crossed over.

36:48.387 --> 36:49.249
Now I'm found.

36:50.771 --> 36:54.376
I was blind, but now I see.

36:55.677 --> 36:56.178
Let's pray.

36:58.882 --> 36:59.903
Lord Jesus, thank you.

37:01.606 --> 37:18.327
Thank you for the amazing undeserved gift of your life for ours, of forgiveness, of your willingness to open a way for us to cross over, something we could not do for ourselves, but a gift you've given us.

37:19.328 --> 37:23.634
Father, for each one of us who has experienced that crossing, we thank you.

37:24.258 --> 37:29.844
And I pray for any of my brothers and sisters this morning that have crossed over but are also at a point where they're tired in the journey.

37:30.645 --> 37:37.192
Lord, I pray to remind them that you are still with them and perhaps you're letting them go through the fight now, but you have not forsaken them.

37:38.313 --> 37:39.294
Give them strength, I pray.

37:41.396 --> 37:53.970
For any of my friends here this morning that have not yet taken that step, but they're looking at and they're thinking about Lord, I pray that you would grant them the faith, the courage to take that step of faith and to

37:54.082 --> 37:57.350
Step into the discovery of what it means to walk with you.

37:59.796 --> 38:04.707
Thank you, Lord, that you haven't left us as slaves, that you have brought us into freedom.

38:06.211 --> 38:07.254
We praise you for that.

38:07.294 --> 38:09.138
In Jesus' name, amen.

